ficials increasingly attached it to the bodies, beliefs, and personhood.Surkis argues that powerful affective attachments to the intimate life of the family and fantasies about Algerian women and the sexual prerogatives of Muslim men, supposedly codified in the practices of polygamy and child marriage, shaped French theories and regulatory practices of Muslim law in fundamental and lasting ways. Women's legal status in particular came to represent the dense relationship between sex and sovereignty in the colony. This book also highlights the ways in which Algerians interacted with and responded to colonial law. Ultimately, this sweeping legal genealogy of French Algeria elucidates how "the Muslim question" in France became—and remains—a question of sex.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 21. Jun 2021) 0aDomestic relations (Islamic law)zAlgeriaxHistory. 0aIslamic lawzAlgeriaxHistory. 0aMuslimsxLegal status, laws, etczAlgeriaxHistory. 0aMuslimsxLegal status, laws, etc.zAlgeriaxHistory. 0aWomenxLegal status, laws, etczAlgeriaxHistory. 0aWomenxLegal status, laws, etc.zAlgeriaxHistory. 4aAfrican Hist & Diaspora. 4aHistory. 4aWest European History. 7aHISTORY / Europe / France.2bisacsh  aSovereignty, Colonial Law, Algeria, Secularism, Fantasy.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertCornell University Press Complete eBook-Package 2019z978311065198008iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2019 Englishz978311061076508iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2019z9783110664232oZDB-23-DGG08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE History 2019 Englishz978311061017808iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE History 2019z9783110606195oZDB-23-DEG40uhttps://doi.org/10.7591/978150173951440uhttps:/